get_page(target_url)[source]¶

Retrieve a specific page of AllTimeInstance records from the API. Request is executed immediately

Return type:twilio.rest.api.v2010.account.usage.record.all_time.AllTimePage
list(category=<object object>, start_date=<object object>, end_date=<object object>, include_subaccounts=<object object>, limit=None, page_size=None)[source]¶

Lists AllTimeInstance records from the API as a list. Unlike stream(), this operation is eager and will load limit records into memory before returning.

Parameters:
  • category (AllTimeInstance.Category) – The usage category of the UsageRecord resources to read
  • start_date (date) – Only include usage that has occurred on or after this date
  • end_date (date) – Only include usage that occurred on or before this date
  • include_subaccounts (bool) – Whether to include usage from the master account and all its subaccounts
  • limit (int) – Upper limit for the number of records to return. list() guarantees never to return more than limit. Default is no limit
  • page_size (int) – Number of records to fetch per request, when not set will use the default value of 50 records. If no page_size is defined but a limit is defined, list() will attempt to read the limit with the most efficient page size, i.e. min(limit, 1000)
Returns:

Generator that will yield up to limit results
Return type:

list[twilio.rest.api.v2010.account.usage.record.all_time.AllTimeInstance]

stream(category=<object object>, start_date=<object object>, end_date=<object object>, include_subaccounts=<object object>, limit=None, page_size=None)[source]¶

Streams AllTimeInstance records from the API as a generator stream. This operation lazily loads records as efficiently as possible until the limit is reached. The results are returned as a generator, so this operation is memory efficient.

Parameters:
  • category (AllTimeInstance.Category) – The usage category of the UsageRecord resources to read
  • start_date (date) – Only include usage that has occurred on or after this date
  • end_date (date) – Only include usage that occurred on or before this date
  • include_subaccounts (bool) – Whether to include usage from the master account and all its subaccounts
  • limit (int) – Upper limit for the number of records to return. stream() guarantees to never return more than limit. Default is no limit
  • page_size (int) – Number of records to fetch per request, when not set will use the default value of 50 records. If no page_size is defined but a limit is defined, stream() will attempt to read the limit with the most efficient page size, i.e. min(limit, 1000)
Returns:

Generator that will yield up to limit results
Return type:

list[twilio.rest.api.v2010.account.usage.record.all_time.AllTimeInstance]

list(category=<object object>, start_date=<object object>, end_date=<object object>, include_subaccounts=<object object>, limit=None, page_size=None)[source]¶

Lists DailyInstance records from the API as a list. Unlike stream(), this operation is eager and will load limit records into memory before returning.

Parameters:
  • category (DailyInstance.Category) – The usage category of the UsageRecord resources to read
  • start_date (date) – Only include usage that has occurred on or after this date
  • end_date (date) – Only include usage that occurred on or before this date
  • include_subaccounts (bool) – Whether to include usage from the master account and all its subaccounts
  • limit (int) – Upper limit for the number of records to return. list() guarantees never to return more than limit. Default is no limit
  • page_size (int) – Number of records to fetch per request, when not set will use the default value of 50 records. If no page_size is defined but a limit is defined, list() will attempt to read the limit with the most efficient page size, i.e. min(limit, 1000)
Returns:

Generator that will yield up to limit results
Return type:

stream(category=<object object>, start_date=<object object>, end_date=<object object>, include_subaccounts=<object object>, limit=None, page_size=None)[source]¶

Streams DailyInstance records from the API as a generator stream. This operation lazily loads records as efficiently as possible until the limit is reached. The results are returned as a generator, so this operation is memory efficient.

Parameters:
  • category (DailyInstance.Category) – The usage category of the UsageRecord resources to read
  • start_date (date) – Only include usage that has occurred on or after this date
  • end_date (date) – Only include usage that occurred on or before this date
  • include_subaccounts (bool) – Whether to include usage from the master account and all its subaccounts
  • limit (int) – Upper limit for the number of records to return. stream() guarantees to never return more than limit. Default is no limit
  • page_size (int) – Number of records to fetch per request, when not set will use the default value of 50 records. If no page_size is defined but a limit is defined, stream() will attempt to read the limit with the most efficient page size, i.e. min(limit, 1000)
Returns:

Generator that will yield up to limit results
Return type:

list(category=<object object>, start_date=<object object>, end_date=<object object>, include_subaccounts=<object object>, limit=None, page_size=None)[source]¶

Lists LastMonthInstance records from the API as a list. Unlike stream(), this operation is eager and will load limit records into memory before returning.

Parameters:
  • category (LastMonthInstance.Category) – The usage category of the UsageRecord resources to read
  • start_date (date) – Only include usage that has occurred on or after this date
  • end_date (date) – Only include usage that occurred on or before this date
  • include_subaccounts (bool) – Whether to include usage from the master account and all its subaccounts
  • limit (int) – Upper limit for the number of records to return. list() guarantees never to return more than limit. Default is no limit
  • page_size (int) – Number of records to fetch per request, when not set will use the default value of 50 records. If no page_size is defined but a limit is defined, list() will attempt to read the limit with the most efficient page size, i.e. min(limit, 1000)
Returns:

Generator that will yield up to limit results
Return type:

stream(category=<object object>, start_date=<object object>, end_date=<object object>, include_subaccounts=<object object>, limit=None, page_size=None)[source]¶

Streams LastMonthInstance records from the API as a generator stream. This operation lazily loads records as efficiently as possible until the limit is reached. The results are returned as a generator, so this operation is memory efficient.

Parameters:
  • category (LastMonthInstance.Category) – The usage category of the UsageRecord resources to read
  • start_date (date) – Only include usage that has occurred on or after this date
  • end_date (date) – Only include usage that occurred on or before this date
  • include_subaccounts (bool) – Whether to include usage from the master account and all its subaccounts
  • limit (int) – Upper limit for the number of records to return. stream() guarantees to never return more than limit. Default is no limit
  • page_size (int) – Number of records to fetch per request, when not set will use the default value of 50 records. If no page_size is defined but a limit is defined, stream() will attempt to read the limit with the most efficient page size, i.e. min(limit, 1000)
Returns:

Generator that will yield up to limit results

list(category=<object object>, start_date=<object object>, end_date=<object object>, include_subaccounts=<object object>, limit=None, page_size=None)[source]¶

Lists MonthlyInstance records from the API as a list. Unlike stream(), this operation is eager and will load limit records into memory before returning.

Parameters:
  • category (MonthlyInstance.Category) – The usage category of the UsageRecord resources to read
  • start_date (date) – Only include usage that has occurred on or after this date
  • end_date (date) – Only include usage that occurred on or before this date
  • include_subaccounts (bool) – Whether to include usage from the master account and all its subaccounts
  • limit (int) – Upper limit for the number of records to return. list() guarantees never to return more than limit. Default is no limit
  • page_size (int) – Number of records to fetch per request, when not set will use the default value of 50 records. If no page_size is defined but a limit is defined, list() will attempt to read the limit with the most efficient page size, i.e. min(limit, 1000)
Returns:

Generator that will yield up to limit results
Return type:

stream(category=<object object>, start_date=<object object>, end_date=<object object>, include_subaccounts=<object object>, limit=None, page_size=None)[source]¶

Streams MonthlyInstance records from the API as a generator stream. This operation lazily loads records as efficiently as possible until the limit is reached. The results are returned as a generator, so this operation is memory efficient.

Parameters:
  • category (MonthlyInstance.Category) – The usage category of the UsageRecord resources to read
  • start_date (date) – Only include usage that has occurred on or after this date
  • end_date (date) – Only include usage that occurred on or before this date
  • include_subaccounts (bool) – Whether to include usage from the master account and all its subaccounts
  • limit (int) – Upper limit for the number of records to return. stream() guarantees to never return more than limit. Default is no limit
  • page_size (int) – Number of records to fetch per request, when not set will use the default value of 50 records. If no page_size is defined but a limit is defined, stream() will attempt to read the limit with the most efficient page size, i.e. min(limit, 1000)
Returns:

Generator that will yield up to limit results
Return type:

list(category=<object object>, start_date=<object object>, end_date=<object object>, include_subaccounts=<object object>, limit=None, page_size=None)[source]¶

Lists ThisMonthInstance records from the API as a list. Unlike stream(), this operation is eager and will load limit records into memory before returning.

Parameters:
  • category (ThisMonthInstance.Category) – The usage category of the UsageRecord resources to read
  • start_date (date) – Only include usage that has occurred on or after this date
  • end_date (date) – Only include usage that occurred on or before this date
  • include_subaccounts (bool) – Whether to include usage from the master account and all its subaccounts
  • limit (int) – Upper limit for the number of records to return. list() guarantees never to return more than limit. Default is no limit
  • page_size (int) – Number of records to fetch per request, when not set will use the default value of 50 records. If no page_size is defined but a limit is defined, list() will attempt to read the limit with the most efficient page size, i.e. min(limit, 1000)
Returns:

Generator that will yield up to limit results
Return type:

Streams ThisMonthInstance records from the API as a generator stream. This operation lazily loads records as efficiently as possible until the limit is reached. The results are returned as a generator, so this operation is memory efficient.

Parameters:
  • category (ThisMonthInstance.Category) – The usage category of the UsageRecord resources to read
  • start_date (date) – Only include usage that has occurred on or after this date
  • end_date (date) – Only include usage that occurred on or before this date
  • include_subaccounts (bool) – Whether to include usage from the master account and all its subaccounts
  • limit (int) – Upper limit for the number of records to return. stream() guarantees to never return more than limit. Default is no limit
  • page_size (int) – Number of records to fetch per request, when not set will use the default value of 50 records. If no page_size is defined but a limit is defined, stream() will attempt to read the limit with the most efficient page size, i.e. min(limit, 1000)

list(category=<object object>, start_date=<object object>, end_date=<object object>, include_subaccounts=<object object>, limit=None, page_size=None)[source]¶

Lists TodayInstance records from the API as a list. Unlike stream(), this operation is eager and will load limit records into memory before returning.

Parameters:
  • category (TodayInstance.Category) – The usage category of the UsageRecord resources to read
  • start_date (date) – Only include usage that has occurred on or after this date
  • end_date (date) – Only include usage that occurred on or before this date
  • include_subaccounts (bool) – Whether to include usage from the master account and all its subaccounts
  • limit (int) – Upper limit for the number of records to return. list() guarantees never to return more than limit. Default is no limit
  • page_size (int) – Number of records to fetch per request, when not set will use the default value of 50 records. If no page_size is defined but a limit is defined, list() will attempt to read the limit with the most efficient page size, i.e. min(limit, 1000)
Returns:

Generator that will yield up to limit results
Return type:

stream(category=<object object>, start_date=<object object>, end_date=<object object>, include_subaccounts=<object object>, limit=None, page_size=None)[source]¶

Streams TodayInstance records from the API as a generator stream. This operation lazily loads records as efficiently as possible until the limit is reached. The results are returned as a generator, so this operation is memory efficient.

Parameters:
  • category (TodayInstance.Category) – The usage category of the UsageRecord resources to read
  • start_date (date) – Only include usage that has occurred on or after this date
  • end_date (date) – Only include usage that occurred on or before this date
  • include_subaccounts (bool) – Whether to include usage from the master account and all its subaccounts
  • limit (int) – Upper limit for the number of records to return. stream() guarantees to never return more than limit. Default is no limit
  • page_size (int) – Number of records to fetch per request, when not set will use the default value of 50 records. If no page_size is defined but a limit is defined, stream() will attempt to read the limit with the most efficient page size, i.e. min(limit, 1000)
Returns:

Generator that will yield up to limit results

list(category=<object object>, start_date=<object object>, end_date=<object object>, include_subaccounts=<object object>, limit=None, page_size=None)[source]¶

Lists YearlyInstance records from the API as a list. Unlike stream(), this operation is eager and will load limit records into memory before returning.

Parameters:
  • category (YearlyInstance.Category) – The usage category of the UsageRecord resources to read
  • start_date (date) – Only include usage that has occurred on or after this date
  • end_date (date) – Only include usage that occurred on or before this date
  • include_subaccounts (bool) – Whether to include usage from the master account and all its subaccounts
  • limit (int) – Upper limit for the number of records to return. list() guarantees never to return more than limit. Default is no limit
  • page_size (int) – Number of records to fetch per request, when not set will use the default value of 50 records. If no page_size is defined but a limit is defined, list() will attempt to read the limit with the most efficient page size, i.e. min(limit, 1000)
Returns:

Generator that will yield up to limit results
Return type:

stream(category=<object object>, start_date=<object object>, end_date=<object object>, include_subaccounts=<object object>, limit=None, page_size=None)[source]¶

Streams YearlyInstance records from the API as a generator stream. This operation lazily loads records as efficiently as possible until the limit is reached. The results are returned as a generator, so this operation is memory efficient.

Parameters:
  • category (YearlyInstance.Category) – The usage category of the UsageRecord resources to read
  • start_date (date) – Only include usage that has occurred on or after this date
  • end_date (date) – Only include usage that occurred on or before this date
  • include_subaccounts (bool) – Whether to include usage from the master account and all its subaccounts
  • limit (int) – Upper limit for the number of records to return. stream() guarantees to never return more than limit. Default is no limit
  • page_size (int) – Number of records to fetch per request, when not set will use the default value of 50 records. If no page_size is defined but a limit is defined, stream() will attempt to read the limit with the most efficient page size, i.e. min(limit, 1000)
Returns:

Generator that will yield up to limit results

list(category=<object object>, start_date=<object object>, end_date=<object object>, include_subaccounts=<object object>, limit=None, page_size=None)[source]¶

Lists YesterdayInstance records from the API as a list. Unlike stream(), this operation is eager and will load limit records into memory before returning.

Parameters:
  • category (YesterdayInstance.Category) – The usage category of the UsageRecord resources to read
  • start_date (date) – Only include usage that has occurred on or after this date
  • end_date (date) – Only include usage that occurred on or before this date
  • include_subaccounts (bool) – Whether to include usage from the master account and all its subaccounts
  • limit (int) – Upper limit for the number of records to return. list() guarantees never to return more than limit. Default is no limit
  • page_size (int) – Number of records to fetch per request, when not set will use the default value of 50 records. If no page_size is defined but a limit is defined, list() will attempt to read the limit with the most efficient page size, i.e. min(limit, 1000)
Returns:

Generator that will yield up to limit results
Return type:

Streams YesterdayInstance records from the API as a generator stream. This operation lazily loads records as efficiently as possible until the limit is reached. The results are returned as a generator, so this operation is memory efficient.

Parameters:
  • category (YesterdayInstance.Category) – The usage category of the UsageRecord resources to read
  • start_date (date) – Only include usage that has occurred on or after this date
  • end_date (date) – Only include usage that occurred on or before this date
  • include_subaccounts (bool) – Whether to include usage from the master account and all its subaccounts
  • limit (int) – Upper limit for the number of records to return. stream() guarantees to never return more than limit. Default is no limit
  • page_size (int) – Number of records to fetch per request, when not set will use the default value of 50 records. If no page_size is defined but a limit is defined, stream() will attempt to read the limit with the most efficient page size, i.e. min(limit, 1000)

list(category=<object object>, start_date=<object object>, end_date=<object object>, include_subaccounts=<object object>, limit=None, page_size=None)[source]¶

Lists RecordInstance records from the API as a list. Unlike stream(), this operation is eager and will load limit records into memory before returning.

Parameters:
  • category (RecordInstance.Category) – The usage category of the UsageRecord resources to read
  • start_date (date) – Only include usage that has occurred on or after this date
  • end_date (date) – Only include usage that occurred on or before this date
  • include_subaccounts (bool) – Whether to include usage from the master account and all its subaccounts
  • limit (int) – Upper limit for the number of records to return. list() guarantees never to return more than limit. Default is no limit
  • page_size (int) – Number of records to fetch per request, when not set will use the default value of 50 records. If no page_size is defined but a limit is defined, list() will attempt to read the limit with the most efficient page size, i.e. min(limit, 1000)
Returns:

Generator that will yield up to limit results
Return type:

stream(category=<object object>, start_date=<object object>, end_date=<object object>, include_subaccounts=<object object>, limit=None, page_size=None)[source]¶

Streams RecordInstance records from the API as a generator stream. This operation lazily loads records as efficiently as possible until the limit is reached. The results are returned as a generator, so this operation is memory efficient.

Parameters:
  • category (RecordInstance.Category) – The usage category of the UsageRecord resources to read
  • start_date (date) – Only include usage that has occurred on or after this date
  • end_date (date) – Only include usage that occurred on or before this date
  • include_subaccounts (bool) – Whether to include usage from the master account and all its subaccounts
  • limit (int) – Upper limit for the number of records to return. stream() guarantees to never return more than limit. Default is no limit
  • page_size (int) – Number of records to fetch per request, when not set will use the default value of 50 records. If no page_size is defined but a limit is defined, stream() will attempt to read the limit with the most efficient page size, i.e. min(limit, 1000)
Returns:

Generator that will yield up to limit results
Return type:
